k and others--and concludes that the evidence doesn't stack up in support of Gaia. Toby Tyrrell draws on the latest findings in fields as diverse as climate science, oceanography, atmospheric science, geology, ecology, and evolutionary biology. He takes readers to obscure corners of the natural world, from southern Africa where ancient rocks reveal that icebergs were once present near the equator, to mimics of cleaner fish on Indonesian reefs, to blind fish deep in Mexican caves. Tyrrell weaves these and many other intriguing observations into a comprehensive analysis of the major assertions and lines of argument underpinning Gaia, and finds that it is not a credible picture of how life and Earth interact. On Gaia reflects on the scientific evidence indicating that life and environment mutually affect each other, and proposes that feedbacks on Earth do not provide robust protection against the environment becoming uninhabitable--or against poor stewardship by us.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aGaia hypothesis. 0aGeobiology. 0aNATURExReference. 0aPhilosophy of nature. 0aSCIENCExEarth SciencesxMeteorology & Climatology. 0aSCIENCExLife SciencesxBiology. 0aSCIENCExLife SciencesxGeneral. 7aSCIENCE / Earth Sciences / General.2bisacsh  aCretaceous.  aEarth climate.  aEarth environment.  aEarth history.  aGaia hypothesis.  aGaia.  aJames Lovelock.  aanaerobes.  aanthropic principle.  aastronomical processes.  aatmosphere.  aatmospheric CO2.  aatmospheric science.  abiodiversity.  abiological processes.  abiomass.  abiosphere.  acarbon.  achemical equilibrium.  aclimate science.  aclimate shifts.  aclimatic state.  acoevolutionary hypothesis.  adiatoms.  aecological dynamics.  aecology.  aenvironmental catastrophes.  aenvironmental control.  aenviro